Text.Value: Only by the full, uninhibited application of psionic stimuli will we have a true measure of whether the child's innate evil has been cured.
What are you going to do with it?
A githyanki sympathiser? I'd no idea their evil could be passed on. Leave our premises - at once!
You don't say? Blurg happens to be upstairs, preparing a most unusual paper. I'm sure he'll be pleased to see a friendly face.
I carry an unhatched githyanki egg. Would you be interested in studying it?
Sell the githyanki egg.
I met an expeditioner claiming to work for you. She sought a githyanki egg.
The Society have studied your kind's brutality for years. You will not find us so easily intimidated.
Not at first. But if the experiment proves successful, it must be repeated. Only then will we know if the findings are to be trusted.
An experiment like this will only confirm the surface dwellers' suspicion of us.
No.
A wonderful research partnership, I'm sure you'll agree. They are upstairs, if you wish to share any theories with them.
You find yourself in the cradle of all knowledge relating to the Underdark: the Society of Brilliance.
Patience does not delay, it simply tempers virtue. Curtails it from excess.
Ah. A display of the well-known githyanki arrogance. I am not sure my experiment can cure that particular affliction, but give me time and I will find a way.
Fine. Here you go.
Attack.
That is a shame. I'll have to find another way to procure a specimen. Or some additional funds.
Now, I'm eager to get started, so will you sell me the egg? ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
Attack.
Once the dust is settled on this whole invading army mess outside the walls, I'll find another contractor. Perhaps they will have more success.
And therein lies your fault: you would have us argue in circles until the egg hatches naturally. Time we do not have.
No benefit could justify you inflicting such cruelty.
No, thanks. I've grown quite attached to it.
As citizens of the Underdark, we face similar stigmas. Totally unfounded, of course - our natures are as unfixed as any who walk the surface.
You yourself have no doubt experienced the prejudice of those who assume that, as beings of the Underdark, we are inherently evil.
Enough of your kind have wreaked destruction on this plane for me to be confident in my assertion.
Was there anything else? I should really get back to my research.
I assume nothing. Innate githyanki cruelty is an established fact - no doubt you witnessed it yourself in the retrieval of the egg itself.
Ah, a visitor from the astral expanse.
Ah, a surface dweller.
I say - that wasn't a githyanki egg you were fiddling around with, was it?

EditorData.NodeContext: Curious, acting casual (he really wants the egg)

Text.Value: Ah, a fellow inhabitor of the Underdark.
Study it, of course. Your kind have been a source of great debate in the Society's circles in recent months.
A series of moral imperatives bestowed by the great dragon-deity Bahamut.
Assuming I can accelerate its growth, I should have conclusive findings within a year or two at the most.
Sell the egg.
By your words, any virtue delaying patience would itself be unvirtuous.
Perhaps not. Patience is important, but cannot impede the other virtues.
Should you grow tired of your responsibilities, do bring the egg to me. I'll gladly take it off your hands.
I assure you, forming any emotional attachment to the gith spawn is quite pointless. It will show you no such affection in return.
Nothing else.
I met one of your researchers in the Underdark. His name was Blurg.
Progress may be delayed, but I assure you - it can never be stopped.
Once out of the shell, I plan to take a twofold approach:
You assume my people are evil, yet your research is built on sheer superstition.
Wonderful. I'll begin making preliminary notes at once.
Tsk'va! To think I trusted you with such a treasure!
Feel free to explore the Lodge. Our knowledge is here for the common good, after all.
Yes, dear Lady Esther. One of our most reliable contractors, though unfortunately this particular request was too much even for her.
My thanks again for retrieving the specimen. It really is a perfect sample.
The Society's doors are always open to those who value knowledge and the proper application of it.
So you're planning to torture a child for a year?
Study it, of course. The githyanki have been a source of great debate in the Society's circles in recent months.
You've provided me with a fine specimen. I'll be sure to mention your name in the footnotes.
What are you playing at, destroying a perfectly good githyanki specimen like that? Utter foolishness.

EditorData.NodeContext: Just saw the player destroy the githyanki egg he wanted. Cna't believe your stupidity

EditorData.logicalname: Alias (Has Egg, doesn't know society wants it, conversation exhausted)

Text.Value: I met two of your researchers in the Underdark - Blurg and Omeluum.
Was there anything else?
Your findings are irrelevant, as are the opinions of all on this kaincha plane.
How would you like to sell it to the Society of Brilliance? ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
I assure you, we are as well-provisioned an institution as any other you'll find in this city. We simply prefer to keep our wealth away from areas of study.

EditorData.NodeContext: Defensive, has heard this accusation before

Text.Value: I don't suppose you'd consider simply donating it to the Society instead?
A githyanki egg? What a fortuitous turn of events. I've been attempting to get my hands on one for some time now.
Most on this plane believe you to be innately cruel, violent beings. Evil, if you will.
Chk. Don't you dare consider it.
Ah. Unfortunately, it seems I've mislaid my purse.
I believe she quite lost her senses over the task. She came here insisting I purchase an owlbear egg from her, of all things.
Tell me, then, philosopher - if patience delays the fostering of the other virtues, can it be rightly called virtuous?

EditorData.NodeContext: sligthly derisive, smug - he's had this argument in his head before and thinks he's absolutely won it with this point

Text.Value: Changed your mind, have you? The offer's still there - a fair price for the spawn, I'd say. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])

EditorData.logicalname: Refused to sell egg, player has egg

Text.Value: I don't suppose you've stumbled across any githyanki eggs during your travels? The Society will compensate you for any we purchase, of course. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
A most intelligent impulse, but I'm afraid it simply isn't possible.
When I have a suitable sample for my study, I will, however, prove that the effects of their biological inclination are reversible.
Then I will source another subject, and the experiment will be completed without your involvement.
Sounds pointless. Public opinion will hardly be swayed by such a small experiment.
You find yourself in the cradle of all knowledge relating to our subterranean home: the Society of Brilliance.
Then we are in accord - the time for action is now.
New memberships are on hold for as long as those wretched Absolutists are banging on the city gates.

EditorData.logicalname: Alias Stole Havkelaag's Gold (Refused to sell egg, player has no egg)

Text.Value: A worthwhile aspiration. You're welcome to the egg.
I knew you weren't Society material. I'll find another means of procuring an egg.

EditorData.logicalname: Refused to sell egg, player has no egg

Text.Value: Any suffering it endures will therefore be worth it, for the child, perhaps for the whole of civilised society.
Rigorous experimental methods demand we do not indulge our own emotional responses in the application of discomfort to our subjects.
'The Society of Brilliance'? Looks like a library to me.
In the literal sense, I will need to induce the egg to hatch via the application of certain currents to the creature inside.
Why follow the dogma of a draconic god?
In my years of study, they're the closest I've found to moral perfection. Only under such rigorous 'goodness' will the subject stand a chance of being cured.
What does this 'intellectually stimulating' upbringing look like?
One must stay humble in order to achieve true academic rigour.
Of course it won't. If anything, it will do quite the opposite. The academic institutions up here will finally be forced to take us seriously.
A cautious, hesitant instinct. One I am afraid we do not have time for.
Shka'keth. You will not live to torment the yank within that shell.

EditorData.logicalname: Alias Hasn't Told About Meeting Expeditioner (Greeting - HasMet Conversation active)

Text.Value: The pursuit of knowledge is neither evil nor good. Only in the application of such knowledge should one take on any moral imperative.
You would teach the child virtue, but rear it without patience. Curious.
I'd no idea your kind were capable of showing such parental instincts.
The child will be a better individual after my treatment than it ever would have been had it been raised in its natural environment.
So the child inside will be experimented on?
No.
You're letting your personal biases affect your method. Why assume they're evil?
I'd like to become a member.
Leave.
You are no doubt aware that citizens of the Underdark are held in great suspicion by those who live above ground. Many believe us to be 'evil'.
Would you consider parting with it? The Society's coffers are deep enough to cover any expenses accrued in its retrieval, of course. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
The githyanki face similar prejudice, but I believe, if hatched in a less violent, more intellectually stimulating environment, the child can overcome its evil predispositions.
The enforced repetition of sound moral principles from the Ptarian code, alongside a series of psionic pulses administered to the cerebral tissue.
Not interested. The egg stays with me.

EditorData.logicalname: Alias (Has Egg, doesn't know society wants it, conversation exhausted)

Text.Value: A gith hatchling is not a lab rat! This shka'keth should be bled dry for the mere suggestion.
My findings could change the perception of your kind and the peoples of the Underdark for generations to come.
My findings could change the perception of githyanki and the peoples of the Underdark for generations to come.
That kind of indoctrination and time-forced nurture violates the natural order. It invalidates the whole experiment.
Tell me, what can the Society do for you?
Leave.
I believe that, if hatched in a morally sound, intellectually stimulating environment, the child can overcome the evil predisposition its githyanki nature bestows.
So you, too, follow the teachings of Bahamut. Why him?
This experiment is barbaric. You're never getting the egg.
And what if your experiment fails?
This experiment is exactly the kind of evil you're trying to disprove.
It does, however, give you plenty of time to prepare your admission thesis. A brisk thirty-thousand words should be more than sufficient.
If the child remains evil after the experiment is concluded, it will be destroyed. Such is the fate of all used specimens.
You'd better get cracking, then. Here's the egg.
Well met. What can the Society of Brilliance do for you?
What's the Ptarian code?
I won't bother to argue with you. An arboreal shaman can't be expected to understand the rigorous protocols of theoretical research.

Synopsis:
Havkelaag is a member of the Society of Brilliance, who is very interested in proving his theory of Genetic Morality.

This dialog only ever plays in case players the gith kid massacre never happens.
